[[File:Patientenlifter.JPG|thumb|A patient lift]]
A '''patient lift''' ('''patient hoist''', '''jack hoist''', '''hydraulic lift''') may be either a '''sling lift''' or '''sit-to-stand lift'''. This is an assistive device that allows [[patient]]s in [[hospital]]s and [[nursing home]]s and people receiving [[home health care]] to be transferred between a bed and a chair or other similar resting places, by the use of electrical or hydraulic power. Sling lifts are used for patients whose mobility is limited. Sling lifts are mobile (or floor) lifts or overhead lifts (suspended from ceiling, wall-mounted or overhead tracks).<ref>{{Cite journal | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=mpKNG260hIgC&pg=PA225&lpg=PA225&dq=%22hoyer+lift%22 | title = Pocket Guide for the Home Care Aide | isbn = 978-0-8342-1161-2 | author1 = Gingerich | first1 = Barbara Stover | last2 = Ondeck | first2 = Deborah Anne | date = 1998-06-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=T_h5ixNOjEEC&pg=RA2-PA484&dq=%22hoyer+lift%22 | title = Delmar's fundamental and advanced nursing skills | isbn = 978-1-4018-1069-6 | author1 = Altman | first1 = Gaylene | date = 2003-07-29}}</ref>
The sling lift has several advantages. It allows heavy patients to be transferred while decreasing stress on caregivers while also reducing the number of nursing staff required to move patients. It also reduces the chance of orthopedic injury from lifting patients.<ref>{{Cite journal | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=6DgTKGcGOwsC&pg=PA621&dq=%22hoyer+lift%22 | title = Nurses' guide to clinical procedures | isbn = 978-0-7817-5379-1 | author1 = Smith-Temple | first1 = Jean | last2 = Johnson | first2 = Joyce Young | date = 2005-02-01}}</ref>
Another kind of sling lift, which is called a ceiling lift, can be permanently installed on the ceiling of a room in order to save space.<ref>{{Cite journal | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=cP5Wi0Idxa0C&pg=PA210&dq=%22hoyer+lift%22 | title = Stroke and the family: A new guide | isbn = 978-0-674-01513-5 | author1 = Stein | first1 = Joel | date = 2004-10-15}}</ref>
Mistakes using patient lifts may result in serious injury and some injuries that have been caused by improper use or malfunction of sling lifts have led to civil lawsuits.<ref>{{Cite journal | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=7Kp-_MhPHPIC&dq=%22hoyer+lift%22&pg=PA327&lpg=PA327&q=hoyer+lift | title = Legal nurse consulting: Principles and practice | isbn = 978-0-8493-1418-6 | author1 = Iyer | first1 = Patricia W | last2 = Consultants | first2 = American Association of Legal Nurse | date = 2002-11-26}}</ref>
