{{Infobox university | name = Sheikh Sayera Khatun Medical College | native_name = শেখ সায়েরা খাতুন মেডিকেল কলেজ | native_name_lang = bn | image = | image_size = | image_alt = | caption = | other_name = SSKMC | former_name = <!-- or: | former_names = --> | established = {{start date|2011}} | type = [[Public university|Public]] [[medical school]] | academic_affiliation = [[University of Dhaka]] | principal = Dr. Liakat Hossain Tapan | director = | academic_staff = | administrative_staff = | students = 300 | undergrad = M.B.B.S | postgrad = | doctoral = | other = | city = [[Gopalganj Sadar Upazila]] | state = | country = [[Bangladesh]] | coor = {{coord|22.9934|N|89.8204|E|region:BD_type:edu|display=inline,title}} | campus = [[Urban area|Urban]] | language = English | website = }} '''Sheikh Sayera Khatun Medical College''' ({{lang-bn|শেখ সায়েরা খাতুন মেডিকেল কলেজ}}) is a [[Public university|government]] [[medical college]] in [[Bangladesh]], established in 2011. It is located in [[Gopalganj, Bangladesh|Gopalganj]]. The college is affiliated with [[Dhaka University]] as a [[constituent college]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.du.ac.bd/list_of_colleges.php|title=List of Constituent Colleges/Institutes under the University of Dhaka|website=University of Dhaka|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141124215439/http://www.du.ac.bd/list_of_colleges.php|archive-date=24 November 2014|access-date=10 January 2017}}</ref>
Sheikh Sayera Khatun Medical College was named after [[Sheikh Sayera Khatun]], mother of [[Sheikh Mujibur Rahman|Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujibur Rahman]], the "Father of the Nation",<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://en.banglapedia.org/index.php?title=Rahman,_Bangabandhu_Sheikh_Mujibur|title=Rahman, Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujibur - Banglapedia|website=en.banglapedia.org|language=en|access-date=2017-11-28}}</ref> and [[grandmother]] of [[Prime minister|Prime Minister]] [[Sheikh Hasina|Sheik Hasina]].
Sheikh Sayera Khatun Medical College began with only 50 students and few [[infrastructure]] facilities. The first step in its creation and expansion was the training of [[Undergraduate education|undergraduate]] students.{{Citation needed|date=March 2017}}
==Organization and administration== In 2014, the Directorate General of Health Services (DGHS) was reportedly unable to attract applicants for lectureships at the college in the basic subjects of [[anatomy]], [[biochemistry]], and [[physiology]]. As a [[Stopgap|stop gap]] measure, the college borrowed teachers from other medical schools in order to keep classes running.<ref>{{cite news |last=Uzzal |first=Moniruzzaman |date=9 March 2014 |title=Young doctors shy away from teaching |url=http://archive.dhakatribune.com/education/2014/mar/09/young-doctors-shy-away-teaching |newspaper=Dhaka Tribune |access-date=10 January 2017}}</ref>
==Entrance examination== Every year, after passing their Higher Secondary School Certificate examinations, nearly 90,000 applicants from all over the country sit for the medical college admission test. The top 3000 students get the opportunity to study at the Sheikh Sayera Khatun Medical College.
